The Remington 3200 has a reputation for being a reliable, durable and accurate shotgun and are highly sought after by collectors and shooters alike. This is a really outstanding example!!

It comes with ~100 rounds of ammo (.300 win mag) - most is standard hunting ammo, but there is ~16 honady match rounds.

amount of use:
The left side of the stock (I am right handed, so the stock on the left side would be towards the body) has a few small scratches that under normal lighting you can't really even see. Also the Butt pad (there is a rubber type thick cusion that came on the butt) shows signs of normal 'use' from rubbing on clothing, etc.. I have taken this rifle hunting with me 3 times in 3 years. Other than that, I have taken it to the range 2 times in the last 3 years. I think I have shot about 4 (20 round) boxes of ammo in total That is the entirety of this gun's use.

Use Case:
This caliber gun is great for medium (deer, even coyote) and even large game (black bear) if you know what load/weight bullets to use. (this gun has the power!)

Accuracy:
The best I have gotten is 1moa out of this setup at the range, and I have not had the trigger adjusted (everything is factory). I believe that if you got a trigger job, this would be quite an accurate rifle (but that is all dependant on the shooter, of course).

title: For Sale:  Sig P229R .40 - 9 mags - 3 holsters
postcontent:
For sale is a used Sig P229R (purchased in 2007) in .40 S&W. This is a NON E2 model with a short extractor and original mainspring and strut. This handgun is DA/SA, and I have swapped out the factory hollow aluminum guide rod with a Bedair stainless guide rod. This adds a tiny amount of weight to the front, so it helps slightly with recoil and is a bit stronger than the factory guide rod - but is mainly just more attractive than the original one. I do also have the factory blue box the gun originally came in.

I also am including 9 standard capacity magazines for the handgun. They are .40/.357Sig 12rd magazines, and each one of them has a brand new Wolff extra strength spring in them. 

The three holsters included are:

1 High Noon Custom - Slide Guard (with lining) OWB cowhide holster. This is a custom made high ride holster with belt loops that fit up to 1 3/4" belts. It has an adjustable tension screw to fine tune the strength of the retention on the holster. If you have never experienced a custom leather holster - it is AMAZING! Mass produced holsters do not have the detailed boning that custom holsters have which does not retain the handgun as well as custom holsters. If you have ever experienced a mass produced leather holster, you know that the leather becomes well-worked and soft within a month or so, but you don't have any of that with the High Noon. It will be just as rigid as it was when it was made forever. 

The second holster is a Bianchi IWB concealment holster. I have carried the Sig in an "appendix carry" position as well as 3:30-4:00 and it works very well. 

The third and final holster is a great range holster. It is the very popular Blackhawk Serpa holster. It includes both the belt attachment and the quick attach pancake attachment. 

If you need ammo I can also make you a deal on Federal HST for CCW - but ammunition is NOT included in the asking price for this listing.

title: For Sale:  RUGER  SECURITY SIX  .357 Magnum     stainless  6 inch
postcontent:
This is Bill Ruger's double action six shot revolver designed to go head-to-head with the Colt Troopers and Pythons and Smith & Wesson model 27's and 28's and other popular .357 magnum revolvers of the 70's and 80's.  It quickly earned a reputation as 'hell-for-stout', and has proven to be far more durable than its vintage competition.  

This is a solid, well built revolver.  This is the more popular stainless steel version (what we need in Oklahoma). The six inch barrel, adjustable rear sights and high visibility front ramp sight make it great for target shooting.  It's got the Houge type rubber grips, which were very popular in the day.  Twenty to thirty years ago, the first thing you did to your new .357 revolver was remove the factory wood grips and install custom Pachmayer or Hogue rubber grips.

I sold my original Security-six and bought a GP100 when they came out.  It was a good gun, but I sold it, and though it took me a couple of months, I bought my Security-six back.  I kept it for over 25 years, and it's now being enjoyed by my nephew, a deputy sheriff.

This is my second Security-six.  I've not used it much at all.  This gun was made in 1982.  Its not a 'safe queen', but it hasn't been abused.  It's in nice shape.

This gun will do nicely with gentle target loads in .38 special, and it will safely handle the most powerful .357 magnum round you care to shoot, and everything in between. 

At my age, I have the guns I want.  I don't deal in guns;  I buy to keep and use.  Things have changed for us, so I am letting my guns go to family, friends or the market.  There are a lot of cheaper guns on the market.  Perhaps you've learned, as I have, that its better to buy quality the first time, and you'll enjoy it from now on.

No trades, thanks.  I'll entertain offers once you've examined this gun and made your evaluation.  This gun is equal or superior to ANY.357 made today, so don't waste our time with silly low offers.  If you only want to pay for a Taurus, go get one; You won't get a Ruger for that price  --  or you won't get mine anyway.

The gun is available as long as this listing is up.

Make: Belgium

Year of Manufacture: circa 1790s 
Caliber: .69-.70

Markings: The top of the barrel is marked with a crown over "B" and a "N" on the side. 
Barrel Length: 9" 
Sights / Optics: The gun has no sights. 
Stock Configuration & Condition: The stock is one piece oiled wood, with brass hardware. The finish is a very old varnish. There are few marks and dings. The stock is in Good overall condition. Type of Finish: Brown & Brass 
Finish Originality: The brown is natural, but it looks like the metal finishes have been cleaned at some point and are pretty rusty but will probably clean up nicely. 
Overall Condition: This handgun retains about 10% of its brown metal finish. The finish is mottled and rusty. The patina is moderate and attractive. The screw heads are not at all worn. The markings are actually sharp. 
Overall, this handgun rates in about Very Good condition. 
Mechanics: The action functions properly with very strong springs. We did not fire this handgun. 
Assessment: These sea service pistols were made in Belgium for export; they were robust pistols, produced around 1790-1800, finding their way to wars and battles around the world in the very early 1800s. There is record of these guns being used in the American War of 1812.
